    <p>Feeback from 2026-02-09<br/>Some DOM changes to the Button component -</p>
    <ul>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- Inside the DOM, the button's icon and label have been wrapped inside a span element.<br/> -- It's do with accessibility. Most often, we'll want to apply the 'aria-hidden' attribute to icons, and <u>not</u> directly into the SVG itself.<br/> -- Introducing the spans now is a minor change; it will future-proof us against vastly more costly overhauls for things like more-complicated accessibility situations and/or internationalisation.<br/> -- Inspect the Primary Default w Text button and the Primary Default w Icon + Text button; I've manually updated those with the span elements.</li>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- The Android icon used in the Storybook introduced an unforeseen weirdsie. You see, that particular file uses both Fill and Stroke to style its colours. And that's why the original Android robots from Storybook now look broken... <br/> - SVG files used elsewhere throughout the site <em>completely</em> freak out if they're styled with both Fill and Stroke. <br/> -- Update: I've updated the Android icon across <u>all</u> instances to only use a `fill` property.</li>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- Small and Large buttons have been introduced as exemplars for Storybook.</li>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- Clarified the role of Primary, Secondary, and Tertiary button variants.</li>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- An exemplar of the Disabled state has been introduced. <br/>I believe (but could be mistaken) that only Primary buttons would ever receive the disabled state; that's because we should only ever need to prevent a user from committing to a primary action.</li>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- An icon-only Primary button cannot ever exist, and has been nuked.</li>
    </ul>
