    <h3 class="new">Recently updated HTML </h3>
    <div class="demo grid-dialogue">
      <span><strong>Task reminder</strong><br/>Seen in the footer.</span>
      {% include "partials/storybook/fs-dialogue-taskReminder-2inches.njk" %}

      <span><strong>End early</strong><br/>Seen in the Category and Product Details layouts, as well as in the Cart overlay.</span>
      {% include "partials/storybook/fs-dialogue-endEarly-2inches.njk" %}

      <span><strong>Checkout - No Need</strong><br/>Seen in the Checkout - Shipping and Payment panels.</span>
      {% include "partials/storybook/fs-dialogue-infoCheckoutNoNeed-2inches.njk" %}

      <span><strong>Checkout - Postscript</strong><br/>Seen in the Checkout - Order Summary panel, once the three other panels have been marked as Complete.</span>
      {% include "partials/storybook/fs-dialogue-infoCheckoutPostscript-2inches.njk" %}
    </div>

    <p>Feedback for 2026-05-16</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Long story short, the syntax of <code>.fs-dialogue-sm</code> and <code>.fs-dialogue-inline</code> became too muddy, especially with the Onboarding and Interview overlays looming. So in the CSS, I've cleaved off each of these dialogue blocks to be their own thing.</li>
      <li>While each component is now its own thing, I target the class names (not the ID property). This is because <code>End Early</code> and <code>Checkout - No Need</code> both appear multiple times on the same page.</li>
      <li>To that end, meet <code>.fs-dialogue.fs-taskReminder</code>, <code>.fs-dialogue.fs-endEarly</code>, <code>.fs-dialogue.fs-infoCheckoutNoNeed</code>, and <code>.fs-dialogue.fs-infoCheckoutPostscript</code>.</li>
      <li>Note: I haven't been through the other instances of the FS Dialogue boxes which were copied over from Storybook yet. They're still using the old class names. </li>
      <li>Looking forward: During early UX tests, people are doing well with "put things in cart". They're not doing well with "go through the checkout". I'd be keen to add some interactivity to <code>End Early</code>, so that if you've added something to your cart, you'll instead get a prompt to go through the Checkout (or back to your 'shopping list').
      </ul>

    <p>Feedback for 2026-05-13</p>
    <ul>

      <li>Very small HTML changes to these Dialogue components thus far; but probably more to come. I don't think <u>I</u> have a good grasp on my own taxonomy / class names. Like, I think the separation between <code>Dialogue</code> and <code>End Early</code> components reflects that the taxonomy isn't right (on my part). It gets even worse when we consider that the <code>Onboarding</code> and <code>Interview</code> panels also use the .fs-dialogue styles. </li>
      <li>I also want to run some colour-contrast tests and implement colour changes.</li>
      <li>Recommendation: Update these as late as practical, and/or let's figure out a plan.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Feedback from 2026-02-09<br/>Some DOM changes to the FS Dialogue component -</p>
    <ul>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- Tweak the 'max-width' style attached to the div wrapper around the FS Dialogue above. There are breakpoints at 300px; 500px; 700px. </li>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- Inside the button, there's been some simplification of the class names.<br/> -- We still use '.fs-btn' within a FS Dialogue; the other modifiers such as '.btn-sm' are now generic.</li>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- FS Dialogue doesn't really use its sizing modifiers any longer; CSS component queries handles all of that now.</li>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- The FS SVG logo is now rendered as an image, as we'll never style it via CSS.</li>
      <li style="padding-block-end: 0.5rem;">- Strategically, the branding for FS and the storefront are now re-united. Under the hood, namespacing continues to separate the things which will always be FS from the things which might get swapped out to suit a client's branding.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

