  <div class="demo-section">
    <header>
      <h2 id="demo-logo-svg">Logo as a SVG symbol</h2>
    </header>
    <h3 class="new">Added to HTML</h3>
    <div class="demo demo-logo">
      {% include "partials/logo/fakesupermarket-logo.njk" %}
      {% include "partials/logo/fakesupermarket-symbol.njk" %}
    </div>
    <p>Inspect the DOM for this explanation to make sense. There are <u>three</u> parts to this - </p>
    <ul>
      <li>The <code>use</code> element which instantiates the SVG symbol so it can be used as an image. It can appear multiple times per page. </use>
      <li>The <code>symbol</code> itself. It must appear once per page, typically at the far end of the page.</li>
      <li>The <code>defs</code> piece – it defines the linear gradient inside the logo. It must also appear once per page, typically at the far end of the page.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>ELI5? The defined linear gradient is referenced by an 'id' property. If a SVG file is simply rendered directly into a page more than once, those id properties will clash because they're unable to be scoped. You end up with the linear-gradient being a flat, incorrect colour.</p>
